Airlines are being accused of price gouging. It follows the collapse of Comair which accounted for around 40-percent of the country's domestic seat capacity. Aviation expert, Desmond Latham discussed this with eNCA's Gareth Edwards. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Have you tried to take a local flight recently? Well, a Joburg to Cape Town return ticket could set you back around R6,000. READ: Comair suspension | Airlines Association says members not deliberately hiking prices Airlines are being accused of price gouging after the collapse of Comair. But aviation expert Desmond Latham says there are many other factors contributing to the price increases. "There are people who want to buy tickets on an urgent basis and the closer to the date, the more it is," Latham said. READ: Comair suspension | Airline needs investor "There's been [a] sharp increase in fuel prices which is the biggest cost for airlines. "Operating costs have gone up. Demand curve has gone up. "Everyone wants to fly after Covid and all of that has created [the] perfect storm."